Please, for the love of Pete, if you are sourcing can wire that you care to buy wire that has a characteristic impedance (z0) of 120 ohms.

If you dont youll start to notice signal degradation for each additional can component you add to your bus.

I faced this exact situation during build season, and I personally settled on using Automation Direct as a supplier (https://www.automationdirect.com/adc/shopping/catalog/bulk_wire_-a-_cable/low_voltage_control_-a-_signal_cable/q7120-1).

Worked great for us (low power splices, RSL, LEDs, and more), though I personally opted for three conductor for the opportunity to use the same wire for any potential PWM stuff (and TTB non-jacketed 22 AWG is also three conductor) which is only $0.05 more expensive than the two conductor jacketed wire (https://www.automationdirect.com/adc/shopping/catalog/bulk_wire_-a-_cable/low_voltage_control_-a-_signal_cable/q7115-1)

I believe I showed you the exact wire at Asheville when talking about LEDs. If you’re looking for jacketed CAN wire/twisted pair wire in a different jacket color, I wasn’t really able to find a good source for 1 twisted pair 22 AWG jacketed wire, so I just bit the bullet and split our two busses into jacketed and unjacketed and strain relieved properly (a given) to prevent any nicks.
